# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: lithium-battery-management
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-balancing] The individual cells in a battery pack naturally have somewhat different capacities, and so, over the course of charge and discharge cycles, may be at a different state of charge (SOC).
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-balancing] Balancing a multi-cell pack helps to maximize capacity and service life of the pack by working to maintain equivalent state-of-charge of every cell, to the degree possible given their different capacities, over the widest possible range.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-balancing] Balancing is only necessary for packs that contain more than one cell in series.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-balancing] Parallel cells will naturally balance since they are directly connected to each other, but groups of parallel wired cells, wired in series (parallel-series wiring) must be balanced between cell groups.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-balancing] To ensure safe operation and prevent hazardous conditions, the battery management system (BMS) continuously tracks critical parameters like temperature and voltage at the individual cell level, detecting any potential deviations that could lead to failure.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-balancing] While current is typically monitored at the pack level to optimize performance, the BMS may include one-shot protection mechanisms at the cell level to rapidly disconnect cells in case of an abnormally high current, such as during a short circuit or other fault conditions.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-balancing] Under normal operation, discharging must stop when any cell first runs out of charge even though other cells may still hold significant charge.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-balancing] Likewise, charging must stop when any cell reaches its maximum safe charging voltage.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-balancing] Failure to do either may cause permanent damage to the cells, or in extreme cases, may drive cells into reverse polarity, cause internal gassing, thermal runaway, or other catastrophic failures.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-balancing] If the cells are not balanced, such that the high and low cutoff are at least aligned with the state of the lowest capacity cell, the energy that can be taken from and returned to the battery will be limited.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-balancing] Because lithium chemistries often permit flexible membrane structures, lithium cells can be deployed in flexible though sealed bags, which permits higher packing densities within a battery pack.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-balancing] When a lithium cell is mistreated, some of the breakdown products (usually of electrolyte chemicals or additives) outgas.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-balancing] Such cells will become 'puffy' and are very much on the way to failure.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-balancing] In sealed lithium-ion cylindrical-format batteries, the same outgassing has caused rather large pressures (800+ psi has been reported); such cells can explode if not provided with a pressure relief mechanism.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-balancing] Compounding the danger is that many lithium cell chemistries include hydrocarbon chemicals (the exact nature of which is typically proprietary), and these are flammable.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-balancing] Therefore, in addition to the risk of cell mistreatment potentially causing an explosion, a simple non-explosive leak can cause a fire.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-balancing] Most battery chemistries have less dramatic, and less dangerous, failure modes.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-balancing] The chemicals in most batteries are often toxic to some degree, but are rarely explosive or flammable; many are corrosive, which accounts for advice to avoid leaving batteries inside equipment for long periods as the batteries may leak and damage the equipment.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-balancing] Lead acid batteries are an exception, for charging them generates hydrogen gas, which can explode if exposed to an ignition source (e.g., a lit cigarette ) and such an explosion will spray sulfuric acid in all directions.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-balancing] Since this is corrosive and potentially blinding, this is a particular danger.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-balancing] In active balancing, the balancer circuit enables transfer of charge between different cells of the battery, i.e., transferring energy from cells with a higher charge to cells with a lower charge.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-balancing] The term *battery regulator* typically refers only to devices that perform passive balancing.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-balancing] A full BMS might include active balancing as well as temperature monitoring, charging, and other features to maximize the life of a battery pack.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-balancing] Typically, the power handled by each DC-DC converter is a few orders of magnitude lower than the power handled by the battery pack as a whole.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-balancing] In passive balancing, energy is drawn from the most charged cell and dissipated as heat, usually through resistors.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-balancing] Passive balancing equalizes the state of charge at some fixed point—usually either "top balanced", with all cells reaching 100% SOC at the same time; or "bottom balanced", with all cells reaching minimum SOC at the same time.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-balancing] Passive balancing is inherently wasteful, with some of the pack's energy spent as heat for the sake of equalizing the state of charge between cells.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-balancing] The build-up of waste heat may also limit the rate at which balancing can occur.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-balancing] In active balancing, energy may be drawn from the most charged cell and transferred to the least charged cells, e.g., through capacitor-based, inductor-based, or DC-DC converters.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-balancing] Active balancing attempts to redistribute energy from cells at full charge to those with a lower state of charge.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-balancing] Energy can be bled from a cell at higher SOC by switching a reservoir capacitor in-circuit with the cell, then disconnecting the capacitor and reconnecting it to a cell with lower SOC, or through a DC-to-DC converter connected across the entire pack.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-balancing] Due to inefficiencies, some energy is still wasted as heat, but not to the same degree.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-balancing] Despite the obvious advantages, the additional cost and complexity of an active balancing topology can be substantial, and doesn't always make sense depending on the application.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-balancing] This has the advantage of reducing pack weight slightly and lowering parasitic draw, as well as permitting multi-point balancing.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] A battery pack built together with a BMS with an external communication data bus is a smart battery pack.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] A smart battery pack must be charged by a smart battery charger.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] Battery thermal management systems can be either passive or active, and the cooling medium can either be air, liquid, or some form of phase change.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] Air cooling is advantageous in its simplicity.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] Such systems can be passive, relying only on the convection of the surrounding air, or active, using fans for airflow.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] Commercially, the Honda Insight and Toyota Prius both use active air cooling of their battery systems.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] The major disadvantage of air cooling is its inefficiency.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] Large amounts of power must be used to operate the cooling mechanism, far more than active liquid cooling.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] The additional components of the cooling mechanism also add weight to the BMS, reducing the efficiency of batteries used for transportation.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] Liquid cooling has a higher natural cooling potential than air cooling as liquid coolants tend to have higher thermal conductivities than air.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] The batteries can either be directly submerged in the coolant or the coolant can flow through the BMS without directly contacting the battery.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] Indirect cooling has the potential to create large thermal gradients across the BMS due to the increased length of the cooling channels.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] This can be reduced by pumping the coolant faster through the system, creating a tradeoff between pumping speed and thermal consistency.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] The central controller of a BMS communicates internally with its hardware operating at a cell level, or externally with high level hardware such as laptops or an HMI.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] Low-voltage centralized BMSes mostly do not have any internal communications.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] Distributed or modular BMSes must use some low-level internal cell–controller (modular architecture) or controller–controller (distributed architecture) communication.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] These types of communications are difficult, especially for high-voltage systems.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] The problem is the voltage shift between cells.The first cell ground signal may be hundreds of volts higher than the other cell ground signal.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] Apart from software protocols, there are two known ways of hardware communication for voltage shifting systems, optical-isolator and wireless communication.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] Another restriction for internal communications is the maximum number of cells.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] For modular architecture, most hardware is limited to a maximum of 255 nodes.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] For high-voltage systems the seeking time of all cells is another restriction, limiting minimum bus speeds and losing some hardware options.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] The cost of modular systems is important, because it may be comparable to the cell price.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] To bypass power limitations of existing USB cables due to heat from electric current, communication protocols implemented in mobile phone chargers for negotiating an elevated voltage have been developed, the most widely used of which are Qualcomm Quick Charge and MediaTek Pump Express.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] More recently, the USB Power Delivery standard aims for a universal negotiation protocol across devices of up to 240 watts.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] A BMS may also feature a precharge system allowing a safe way to connect the battery to different loads and eliminating the excessive inrush currents to load capacitors.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] The connection to loads is normally controlled through electromagnetic relays called contactors.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] The precharge circuit can be either power resistors connected in series with the loads until the capacitors are charged.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] Alternatively, a switched mode power supply connected in parallel to loads can be used to charge the voltage of the load circuit up to a level close enough to the battery voltage in to allow closing the contactors between the battery and load circuit.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] A BMS may have a circuit that can check whether a relay is already closed before recharging (due to welding for example) to prevent inrush currents from occurring.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] In order to maximize the battery's capacity, and to prevent localized under-charging or over-charging, the BMS may actively ensure that all the cells that compose the battery are kept at the same voltage or State of Charge, through balancing.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] Some chargers accomplish the balance by charging each cell independently.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] This is often performed by the BMS and not the charger (which typically provides only the bulk charge current, and does not interact with the pack at the cell-group level), e.g., e-bike and hoverboard chargers.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] In this method, the BMS will request a lower charge current (such as EV batteries), or will shut-off the charging input (typical in portable electronics) through the use of transistor circuitry while balancing is in effect (to prevent over-charging cells).
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] Centralized BMSs are the most economical, least expandable, and are plagued by a multitude of wires.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] Distributed BMSs are the most expensive, simplest to install, and offer the cleanest assembly.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] Modular BMSes offer a compromise of the features and problems of the other two topologies.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] In the case of electric or hybrid vehicles, the BMS is only a subsystem and cannot work as a stand-alone device.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] It must communicate with at least a charger (or charging infrastructure), a load, thermal management and emergency shutdown subsystems.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] Therefore, in a good vehicle design the BMS is tightly integrated with those subsystems.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] Some small mobile applications (such as medical equipment carts, motorized wheelchairs, scooters, and forklifts) often have external charging hardware, however the on board BMS must still have tight design integration with the external charger.
[src:lithium-battery-management/battery-management-system] Various battery balancing methods are in use, some of them based on state of charge theory.
[src:lithium-battery-management/depth-of-discharge] 2. the fraction of the battery's capacity which is *currently* removed from the battery with regard to its (fully) charged state.
[src:lithium-battery-management/depth-of-discharge] For fully charged batteries, the depth of discharge is connected to the state of charge by the simple formula $\mathrm {DoD} =1-\mathrm {SoC}$ .
[src:lithium-battery-management/depth-of-discharge] The depth of discharge then is the complement of state of charge: as one increases, the other decreases.
[src:lithium-battery-management/depth-of-discharge] This definition is mostly found in scientific sources.
[src:lithium-battery-management/depth-of-discharge] The depth of discharge can therefore (1) refer to the size of the range usually used for discharge or (2) the *current* amount of charge or fraction of the capacity removed from the battery.
[src:lithium-battery-management/depth-of-discharge] To avoid confusion, the exact meaning of DoD should be clear for a given context.
[src:lithium-battery-management/depth-of-discharge] Also, for both definitions, it remains undefined, whether a charged battery's SoC is 100 % or another value.
[src:lithium-battery-management/depth-of-discharge] This reference value is needed to fully describe (1) the *upper and lower limit* of absolute SoC used for operation or (2) the *current value* of the absolute SoC.
[src:lithium-battery-management/depth-of-discharge] During their use, secondary batteries are repeatedly charged and discharged within a certain range of state of charge.
[src:lithium-battery-management/depth-of-discharge] For many battery types, it is beneficial or even mandatory for safety reasons, to not encounter overcharging and/or deep discharge.
[src:lithium-battery-management/depth-of-discharge] To prevent adverse effects, a battery management system or battery charger may keep the battery from extreme levels regarding SoC, thereby limiting the SoC to a reduced range between 0 % and 100 % and decreasing *depth of discharge* below 100 % (see example below).
[src:lithium-battery-management/depth-of-discharge] This corresponds to the DoD in the sense of definition (1).
[src:lithium-battery-management/depth-of-discharge] For almost all known rechargeable battery technologies, such as lead-acid batteries of all kinds like AGM, there is a correlation between the depth of discharge and the cycle life of the battery.
[src:lithium-battery-management/depth-of-discharge] For LiFePO 4 batteries, for example, the state of charge is often limited to the range between 15 % and 85 % to greatly increase their cycle life, resulting in a DoD of 70 %.
[src:lithium-battery-management/depth-of-discharge] While the state of charge is usually expressed using percentage points (0 % = empty; 100 % = full), depth of discharge is either expressed using units of Ah (e.g. for a 50 Ah battery, 0 Ah is full and 50 Ah is empty) or percentage points (100 % is empty and 0 % is full).
[src:lithium-battery-management/depth-of-discharge] The capacity of a battery may also be higher than its nominal rating.
[src:lithium-battery-management/depth-of-discharge] Thus it is possible for the depth of discharge value to exceed the nominal value (e.g., 55 Ah for a 50 Ah battery, or 110 %).
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] A **lithium-ion battery** or **Li-ion battery** is a type of rechargeable battery that uses the reversible intercalation of Li+ ions into electronically conducting solids to store energy.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] There are many different varieties, which are usually categorized by the materials used in the cathode.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Compared to other types of rechargeable batteries, they generally have higher specific energy, energy density, and energy efficiency and a longer cycle life and calendar life.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In the three decades since Li-ion batteries were first sold in 1991, their volumetric energy density increased threefold while their cost dropped tenfold.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In late 2024, global demand passed 1 terawatt-hour per year, while production capacity was more than twice that.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The invention and commercialization of Li-ion batteries has had a large impact on technology, as recognized by the 2019 Nobel Prize in Chemistry, which was awarded to contributors to the development of Li-ion batteries.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Li-ion batteries have enabled portable consumer electronics, laptop computers, cellular phones, and electric cars.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] They are used for grid-scale energy storage and in military and aerospace applications.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Li-ion battery sizes are generally not standardised (e.g. in the spirit of the AA battery) and they come in various and unique form factors depending on device and vendor.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] They typically have a nominal voltage of 3.6 or 3.7 V.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Stanley Whittingham conceived intercalation electrodes in the 1970s and created the first rechargeable lithium-ion battery, based on a titanium disulfide cathode and a lithium-aluminium anode, although it suffered from safety problems and was never commercialized.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] John Goodenough expanded on this work in 1980 by using lithium cobalt oxide as a cathode.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The first prototype of the modern Li-ion battery, which uses a carbonaceous anode rather than lithium metal, was developed by Akira Yoshino in 1985 and commercialized by a Sony and Asahi Kasei team led by Yoshio Nishi in 1991.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Whittingham, Goodenough, and Yoshino were awarded the 2019 Nobel Prize in Chemistry for their contributions to the development of lithium-ion batteries.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium-ion batteries can be a fire or explosion hazard as they contain flammable electrolytes.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Progress has been made in the development and manufacturing of safer lithium-ion batteries.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium-ion solid-state batteries are being developed to eliminate the flammable electrolyte.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium and other minerals can have significant issues in mining, with lithium being water intensive in often arid regions and other minerals used in some Li-ion chemistries potentially being conflict minerals such as cobalt.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Environmental issues have encouraged some researchers to improve mineral efficiency and find alternatives such as lithium iron phosphate lithium-ion chemistries or non-lithium-based battery chemistries such as sodium-ion and iron-air batteries.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium-ion cells can be manufactured to optimize energy density or power density.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Handheld electronics mostly use lithium polymer batteries (with a polymer gel as an electrolyte), a lithium cobalt oxide (LiCoO 2) cathode material, and a graphite anode, which together offer high energy density.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium iron phosphate (LiFePO 4), lithium manganese oxide (LiMn 2O 4 spinel, or Li 2MnO 3-based lithium-rich layered materials, LMR-NMC), and lithium nickel manganese cobalt oxide (LiNiMnCoO 2 or NMC) may offer longer life and a higher discharge rate.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] NMC and its derivatives are widely used in the electrification of transport, one of the main technologies (combined with renewable energy) for reducing greenhouse gas emissions from vehicles.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium nickel cobalt aluminum oxide (NCA) is another high-energy lithium-ion chemistry commonly used in electric vehicle batteries.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] One of the earliest examples of research into lithium-ion batteries is a CuF 2/Li battery developed by NASA in 1965.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The breakthrough that produced the earliest form of the modern Li-ion battery was made by British chemist M.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Stanley Whittingham in 1974, who first used titanium disulfide (TiS 2) as a cathode material, which has a layered structure that can take in lithium ions without significant changes to its crystal structure.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Exxon tried to commercialize this battery in the late 1970s, but found the synthesis expensive and complex, as TiS 2 is sensitive to moisture and releases toxic hydrogen sulfide (H 2S) gas on contact with water.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] More prohibitively, the batteries were also prone to spontaneously catch fire due to the presence of metallic lithium in the cells.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] For this, and other reasons, Exxon discontinued the development of Whittingham's lithium-titanium disulfide battery.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In 1980, working in separate groups Ned A.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Godshall et al., and, shortly thereafter, Koichi Mizushima and John B.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Goodenough, after testing a range of alternative materials, replaced TiS 2 with lithium cobalt oxide (LiCoO 2, or LCO), which has a similar layered structure but offers a higher voltage and is much more stable in air.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] This material would later be used in the first commercial Li-ion battery, although it did not, on its own, resolve the persistent issue of flammability.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] These early attempts to develop rechargeable Li-ion batteries used lithium metal anodes, which were ultimately abandoned due to safety concerns, as lithium metal is unstable and prone to dendrite formation, which can cause short-circuiting.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The eventual solution was to use an intercalation anode, similar to that used for the cathode, which prevents the formation of lithium metal during battery charging.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The first to demonstrate lithium ion reversible intercalation into graphite anodes was Jürgen Otto Besenhard in 1974.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Besenhard used organic solvents such as carbonates, however these solvents decomposed rapidly providing short battery cycle life.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Later, in 1980, Rachid Yazami used a solid organic electrolyte, polyethylene oxide, which was more stable.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In 1985, Akira Yoshino at Asahi Kasei Corporation discovered that petroleum coke, a less graphitized form of carbon, can reversibly intercalate Li-ions at a low potential of ~0.5 V relative to Li+ /Li without structural degradation.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Its structural stability originates from its amorphous carbon regions, which serve as covalent joints to pin the layers together.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Although it has a lower capacity compared to graphite (~Li0.5C6, 186 mAh g–1), it became the first commercial intercalation anode for Li-ion batteries owing to its cycling stability.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In 1987, Yoshino patented what would become the first commercial lithium-ion battery using this anode.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] He used Goodenough's previously reported LiCoO2 as the cathode and a carbonate ester-based electrolyte.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The battery was assembled in the discharged state, which made it safer and cheaper to manufacture.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In 1991, using Yoshino's design, Sony began producing and selling the world's first rechargeable lithium-ion batteries.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The following year, a joint venture between Toshiba and Asahi Kasei Co. also released a lithium-ion battery.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Significant improvements in energy density were achieved in the 1990s by replacing Yoshino's soft carbon anode first with hard carbon and later with graphite.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In 1990, Jeff Dahn and two colleagues at Dalhousie University (Canada) reported reversible intercalation of lithium ions into graphite in the presence of ethylene carbonate solvent (which is solid at room temperature and is mixed with other solvents to make a liquid).
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] This represented the final innovation of the era that created the basic design of the modern lithium-ion battery.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In 2010, global lithium-ion battery production capacity was 20 gigawatt-hours.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] By 2016, it was 28 GWh, with 16.4 GWh in China.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Global production capacity was 767 GWh in 2020, with China accounting for 75%.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Production in 2021 is estimated by various sources to be between 200 and 600 GWh, and predictions for 2023 range from 400 to 1,100 GWh.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Goodenough, Rachid Yazami and Akira Yoshino received the 2012 IEEE Medal for Environmental and Safety Technologies for developing the lithium-ion battery; Goodenough, Whittingham, and Yoshino were awarded the 2019 Nobel Prize in Chemistry "for the development of lithium-ion batteries".
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Jeff Dahn received the ECS Battery Division Technology Award (2011) and the Yeager award from the International Battery Materials Association (2016).
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium-ion batteries are constructed of several key components, including an anode, cathode, separator, casing, electrolyte, and a pair of current collectors.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Typically, the negative electrode of a conventional lithium-ion cell is made from graphite.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The positive electrode is typically a metal oxide or phosphate.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The electrolyte is a lithium salt in an organic solvent.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The negative electrode (which is the anode when the cell is discharging) and the positive electrode (which is the cathode when discharging) are prevented from shorting by a separator.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The electrodes are connected to the powered circuit through two pieces of metal called current collectors.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The negative and positive electrodes swap their electrochemical roles (anode and cathode) when the cell is charged.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Despite this, in discussions of battery design the negative electrode of a rechargeable cell is often just called "the anode" and the positive electrode "the cathode".
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In its fully lithiated state of LiC6, graphite correlates to a theoretical capacity of 1339 coulombs per gram (372 mAh/g).
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The positive electrode is generally one of three materials: a layered oxide (such as lithium cobalt oxide), a polyanion (such as lithium iron phosphate) or a spinel (such as lithium manganese oxide).
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] More experimental materials include graphene-containing electrodes, although these remain far from commercially viable due to their high cost.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium reacts vigorously with water to form lithium hydroxide (LiOH) and hydrogen gas.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Thus, a non-aqueous electrolyte is typically used, and a sealed container rigidly excludes moisture from the battery pack.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The non-aqueous electrolyte is typically a mixture of organic carbonates such as ethylene carbonate and propylene carbonate containing complexes of lithium ions.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Ethylene carbonate is essential for making solid electrolyte interphase on the carbon anode, but since it is solid at room temperature, a liquid solvent (such as propylene carbonate or diethyl carbonate) is added.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The electrolyte salt is almost always lithium hexafluorophosphate (LiPF 6), which combines good ionic conductivity with chemical and electrochemical stability.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The hexafluorophosphate anion is essential for passivating the aluminium current collector used for the positive electrode.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] A titanium tab is ultrasonically welded to the aluminium current collector.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Copper (with a spot-welded nickel tab) is used as the current collector at the negative electrode.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Current collector design and surface treatments may take various forms: foil, mesh, foam (dealloyed), etched (wholly or selectively), and coated (with various materials) to improve electrical characteristics.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Depending on materials choices, the voltage, energy density, life, and safety of a lithium-ion cell can change dramatically.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Current effort has been exploring the use of novel architectures using nanotechnology to improve performance.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Areas of interest include nano-scale electrode materials and alternative electrode structures.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The reactants in the electrochemical reactions in a lithium-ion cell are the materials of the electrodes, both of which are compounds containing lithium atoms.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Although many thousands of different materials have been investigated, only a very small number are commercially usable.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] All commercial Li-ion cells use intercalation compounds as active materials.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The negative electrode is usually graphite, although silicon is often mixed in to increase the capacity.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The electrolyte is usually lithium hexafluorophosphate, dissolved in a mixture of organic carbonates.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] A number of different materials are used for the positive electrode, such as LiCoO2, LiFePO4, and lithium nickel manganese cobalt oxides.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] During cell discharge the negative electrode is the anode and the positive electrode the cathode: electrons flow from the anode to the cathode through the external circuit.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] An oxidation half-reaction at the anode produces positively charged lithium ions and negatively charged electrons.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The oxidation half-reaction may also produce uncharged material that remains at the anode.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium ions move through the electrolyte; electrons move through the external circuit toward the cathode where they recombine with the cathode material in a reduction half-reaction.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The electrolyte provides a conductive medium for lithium ions but does not partake in the electrochemical reaction.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The reactions during discharge lower the chemical potential of the cell, so discharging transfers energy from the cell to wherever the electric current dissipates its energy, mostly in the external circuit.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] During charging these reactions and transports go in the opposite direction: electrons move from the positive electrode to the negative electrode through the external circuit.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] To charge the cell the external circuit has to provide electrical energy.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] This energy is then stored as chemical energy in the cell (with some loss, e. g., due to coulombic efficiency lower than 1).
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Both electrodes allow lithium ions to move in and out of their structures with a process called *insertion* (*intercalation*) or *extraction* (*deintercalation*), respectively.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] As the lithium ions "rock" back and forth between the two electrodes, these batteries are also known as "rocking-chair batteries" or "swing batteries" (a term given by some European industries).
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The following equations exemplify the chemistry (left to right: discharging, right to left: charging).
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The cell's energy is equal to the voltage times the charge.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Each gram of lithium represents Faraday's constant/6.941, or 13,901 coulombs.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] At 3 V, this gives 41.7 kJ per gram of lithium, or 11.6 kWh per kilogram of lithium.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] This is slightly more than the heat of combustion of gasoline; however, lithium-ion batteries as a whole are still significantly heavier per unit of energy due to the additional materials used in production.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Note that the cell voltages involved in these reactions are larger than the potential at which an aqueous solutions would electrolyze.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] During discharge, lithium ions (Li+ ) carry the current within the battery cell from the negative to the positive electrode, through the non-aqueous electrolyte and separator diaphragm.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] During charging, an external electrical power source applies an over-voltage (a voltage greater than the cell's own voltage) to the cell, forcing electrons to flow from the positive to the negative electrode.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The lithium ions also migrate (through the electrolyte) from the positive to the negative electrode where they become embedded in the porous electrode material in a process known as intercalation.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Constant current constant voltage (CC/CV) is the standard method used to charge lithium-ion cells.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] During the constant current phase, the charger applies a constant current to the battery at a steadily increasing voltage.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Once the maximum charging voltage is reached, the charger changes to the constant voltage phase, where the voltage is held steady and the current gradually decreases, until a minimum current threshold is reached.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] If the starting voltage of the cell voltage is too low, a very low charging current is usually used until the voltage reaches a safe level.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] This is sometimes referred to as trickle charging.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] When charging lithium-ion batteries made of multiple cells in series, top-balancing is also often performed.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Failure to follow current and voltage limitations can result in excessive coulombic heating of the battery, and in the case of overcharge to voltages higher than designed can lead to an explosion.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Charging temperature limits for Li-ion are stricter than the operating limits.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium-ion chemistry performs well at elevated temperatures but prolonged exposure to heat reduces battery life.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Li‑ion batteries offer good charging performance at cooler temperatures and may even allow "fast-charging" within a temperature range of 5 to 45 °C (41 to 113 °F).
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Charging should be performed within this temperature range.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] At temperatures from 0 to 5 °C charging is possible, but the charge current should be reduced.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] During a low-temperature (under 0 °C) charge, the slight temperature rise above ambient due to the internal cell resistance is beneficial.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] High temperatures during charging may lead to battery degradation and charging at temperatures above 45 °C will degrade battery performance, whereas at lower temperatures the internal resistance of the battery may increase, resulting in slower charging and thus longer charging times.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Batteries gradually self-discharge even if not connected and delivering current.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Li-ion rechargeable batteries have a self-discharge rate typically stated by manufacturers to be 1.5–2% per month.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The rate increases with temperature and state of charge.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] A 2004 study found that for most cycling conditions self-discharge was primarily time-dependent; however, after several months of stand on open circuit or float charge, state-of-charge dependent losses became significant.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The self-discharge rate did not increase monotonically with state-of-charge, but dropped somewhat at intermediate states of charge.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Self-discharge rates may increase as batteries age.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] By 2007, monthly self-discharge rate was estimated at 2% to 3%, and 2–3% by 2016.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] By comparison, the self-discharge rate for NiMH batteries dropped, as of 2017, from up to 30% per month for previously common cells to about 0.08–0.33% per month for low self-discharge NiMH batteries, and is about 10% per month in NiCd batteries.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium-ion batteries may have multiple levels of structure.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Small batteries consist of a single battery cell.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Larger batteries connect cells in parallel into a module and connect modules in series and parallel into a pack.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Multiple packs may be connected in series to increase the voltage.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Batteries may be equipped with temperature sensors, heating/cooling systems, voltage regulator circuits, voltage taps, and charge-state monitors.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] These components address safety risks like overheating and short circuiting.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] On the macrostructral level (length scale 0.1–5 mm) almost all commercial lithium-ion batteries comprise foil current collectors (aluminium for cathode and copper for anode).
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Copper is selected for the anode, because lithium does not alloy with it.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Aluminum is used for the cathode, because it passivates in LiPF6 electrolytes.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Cells with a cylindrical shape are made in a characteristic "swiss roll" manner (known as a "jelly roll" in the US), which means it is a single long "sandwich" of the positive electrode, separator, negative electrode, and separator rolled into a single spool.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] One advantage of cylindrical cells is faster production speed.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] One disadvantage can be a large radial temperature gradient at high discharge rates.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The absence of a case gives pouch cells the highest gravimetric energy density; however, many applications require containment to prevent expansion when their state of charge (SOC) level is high, and for general structural stability.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Both rigid plastic and pouch-style cells are sometimes referred to as prismatic cells due to their rectangular shapes.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Three basic battery types are used in 2020s-era electric vehicles: cylindrical cells (e.g., Tesla), prismatic pouch (e.g., from LG), and prismatic can cells (e.g., from LG, Samsung, Panasonic, and others).
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium-ion flow batteries have been demonstrated that suspend the cathode or anode material in an aqueous or organic solution.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] As of 2014, the smallest Li-ion cell was pin-shaped with a diameter of 3.5 mm and a weight of 0.6 g, made by Panasonic.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] A coin cell form factor is available for LiCoO2 cells, usually designated with a "LiR" prefix.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The average voltage of LCO (lithium cobalt oxide) chemistry is 3.6 V if made with hard carbon anode and 3.7 V if made with graphite anode.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Comparatively, the latter has a flatter discharge voltage curve.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium-ion batteries are used in a multitude of applications, including consumer electronics, toys, power tools, electric vehicles and backup power in telecommunications applications.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium-ion batteries are also used for grid energy storage.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Some submarines have also been equipped with lithium-ion batteries.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Because lithium-ion batteries can have a variety of positive and negative electrode materials, the energy density and voltage vary accordingly.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The open-circuit voltage is higher than in aqueous batteries (such as lead–acid, nickel–metal hydride and nickel–cadmium).
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Internal resistance increases with both cycling and age, although this depends strongly on the voltage and temperature the batteries are stored at.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Rising internal resistance causes the voltage at the terminals to drop under load, which reduces the maximum current draw.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Eventually, increasing resistance will leave the battery in a state such that it can no longer support the normal discharge currents requested of it without unacceptable voltage drop or overheating.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Batteries with a lithium iron phosphate positive and graphite negative electrodes have a nominal open-circuit voltage of 3.2 V and a typical charging voltage of 3.6 V.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium nickel manganese cobalt (NMC) oxide positives with graphite negatives have a 3.7 V nominal voltage with a 4.2 V maximum while charging.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The charging procedure is performed at constant voltage with current-limiting circuitry (i.e., charging with constant current until a voltage of 4.2 V is reached in the cell and continuing with a constant voltage applied until the current drops close to zero).
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Typically, the charge is terminated at 3% of the initial charge current.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In the past, lithium-ion batteries could not be fast-charged and needed at least two hours to fully charge.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Current-generation cells can be fully charged in 45 minutes or less.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In 2015 researchers demonstrated a small 600 mAh capacity battery charged to 68 percent capacity in two minutes and a 3,000 mAh battery charged to 48 percent capacity in five minutes.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The latter battery has an energy density of 620 W·h/L.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The device employed heteroatoms bonded to graphite molecules in the anode.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Performance of manufactured batteries has improved over time.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] For example, from 1991 to 2005 the energy capacity per price of lithium-ion batteries improved more than ten-fold, from 0.3 W·h per dollar to over 3 W·h per dollar.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In the period from 2011 to 2017, progress has averaged 7.5% annually.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Overall, between 1991 and 2024, prices for all types of lithium-ion cells (in dollars per kWh) fell approximately 99%.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] From 1991 to 2018, energy density more than tripled.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Efforts to increase energy density contributed significantly to cost reduction.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Energy density can also be increased by improvements in the chemistry of the cell, for instance, by full or partial replacement of graphite with silicon.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Silicon anodes enhanced with graphene nanotubes to eliminate the premature degradation of silicon allow for record-breaking battery energy density of up to 350 Wh/kg and lowering EV prices to be competitive with ICEs.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Differently sized cells of the same format (shape) with the same chemistry may have different energy densities.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Jelly roll cells usually have a higher energy density than coin or prismatic cells of the same Ah, because of a tighter/compresses packing of the cell layers.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Among cylindrical cells, those with a larger size have a larger energy density, albeit the exact value strongly depends on the thickness of the electrode layers.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The disadvantage of large cells is decrease of the heat transfer from the cell to its surroundings.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The table below shows the result of an experimental evaluation of a "high-energy" type 3.0 Ah 18650 NMC cell in 2021, round-trip efficiency which compared the energy going into the cell and energy extracted from the cell from 100% (4.2v) SoC to 0% SoC (cut off 2.0v).
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] A round-trip efficiency is the percent of energy that can be used relative to the energy that went into charging the battery.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The lifespan of a lithium-ion battery is typically defined as the number of full charge-discharge cycles to reach a failure threshold in terms of capacity loss or impedance rise.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Manufacturers' datasheets typically uses the word "cycle life" to specify lifespan in terms of the number of cycles to reach 80% of the rated battery capacity.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Simply storing lithium-ion batteries in the charged state also reduces their capacity (the amount of cyclable Li+) and increases the cell resistance (primarily due to the continuous growth of the solid electrolyte interface on the anode).
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Calendar life is used to represent the whole life cycle of battery involving both the cycle and inactive storage operations.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Battery cycle life is affected by many different stress factors including temperature, discharge current, charge current, and state of charge ranges (depth of discharge).
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Batteries are not fully charged and discharged in real applications such as smartphones, laptops and electric cars and hence defining battery life via full discharge cycles can be misleading.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] To avoid this confusion, researchers sometimes use cumulative discharge defined as the total amount of charge (Ah) delivered by the battery during its entire life or equivalent full cycles, which represents the summation of the partial cycles as fractions of a full charge-discharge cycle.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Battery degradation during storage is affected by temperature and battery state of charge (SOC) and a combination of full charge (100% SOC) and high temperature (usually > 50 °C) can result in a sharp capacity drop and gas generation.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Multiplying the battery cumulative discharge by the rated nominal voltage gives the total energy delivered over the life of the battery.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] From this one can calculate the cost per kWh of the energy (including the cost of charging).
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Over their lifespan, batteries degrade gradually leading to reduced cyclable charge (a.k.a.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Ah capacity) and increased resistance (the latter translates into a lower operating cell voltage).
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Also, battery life in room temperature is maximal.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] High charge levels also hasten capacity loss.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Frequent charge to > 90% and discharge to < 10% may also hasten capacity loss.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Keeping the li-ion battery status to about 60% to 80% can reduce the capacity loss.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In a study, scientists provided 3D imaging and model analysis to reveal main causes, mechanics, and potential mitigations of the problematic degradation of the batteries over charge cycles.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium metal plating also results in the loss of lithium inventory (cyclable Ah charge), as well as internal short-circuiting and ignition of a battery.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Once Li plating commences during cycling, it results in larger slopes of capacity loss per cycle and resistance increase per cycle.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] This degradation mechanism become more prominent during fast charging and low temperatures.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Loss of the (negative or positive) electroactive materials due to dissolution (e.g. of Mn3+ species), cracking, exfoliation, detachment or even simple regular volume change during cycling.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] It shows up as both charge and power fade (increased resistance).
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Both positive and negative electrode materials are subject to fracturing due to the volumetric strain of repeated (de)lithiation cycles.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Structural degradation of cathode materials, such as Li+/Ni2+ cation mixing in nickel-rich materials.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] This manifests as "electrode saturation", loss of cyclable Ah charge and as a "voltage fade".
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Negative copper current collector is particularly prone to corrosion/dissolution at low cell voltages.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] PVDF binder also degrades, causing the detachment of the electroactive materials, and the loss of cyclable Ah charge.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] These are shown in the figure on the right.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] A change from one main degradation mechanism to another appears as a knee (slope change) in the capacity vs. cycle number plot.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Most studies of lithium-ion battery aging have been done at elevated (50–60 °C) temperatures for accelerated aging.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Under these storage conditions, fully charged nickel-cobalt-aluminum and lithium-iron phosphate cells lose ca.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] 20% of their cyclable charge in 1–2 years.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] It is believed that the aforementioned anode aging is the most important degradation pathway in these cases.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] On the other hand, manganese-based cathodes show a (ca.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] 20–50%) faster degradation under these conditions, probably due to the additional mechanism of Mn ion dissolution.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] At 25 °C the degradation of lithium-ion batteries seems to follow the same pathway(s) as the degradation at 50 °C, but with half the speed.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In other words, based on the limited extrapolated experimental data, lithium-ion batteries are expected to lose irreversibly around 20% of their cyclable charge in 3–5 years or 1000–2000 cycles at 25 °C.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium-ion batteries with titanate anodes do not suffer from SEI growth, and last longer (>5000 cycles) than graphite anodes.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] However, in complete cells other degradation mechanisms (i.e. the dissolution of Mn3+ and the Ni2+/Li+ place exchange, decomposition of PVDF binder and particle detachment) show up after 1000–2000 days, and the use titanate anode does not improve full cell durability in practice.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium plating is a phenomenon in which certain conditions lead to metallic lithium forming and depositing onto the surface of the battery's anode rather than intercalating within the anode material's structure.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Low temperatures, overcharging and high charging rates can exacerbate this occurrence.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] During these conditions, lithium ions may not intercalate uniformly into the anode material and form layers of lithium ion on the surface in the form of dendrites.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] **Lithium dendrites** are tiny needle-like structures that can accumulate and pierce the separator, causing a short circuit can initiate thermal runaway.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] This cascade of rapid and uncontrolled energy can lead to battery swelling, increased heat, fires and or explosions.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Additionally, this dendritic growth can lead to side reactions with the electrolyte and convert the fresh plated lithium into electrochemically inert dead lithium.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Moreover, the dendritic growth brought on by lithium plating can degrade the lithium-ion battery and lead to poor cycling efficiency and safety hazards.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Some ways to mitigate lithium plating and the dendritic growth is by controlling the temperature, optimizing the charging conditions, and improving the materials used.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In terms of temperature, the ideal charging temperature is anywhere between 0 °C to 45 °C, but also room temperature is ideal (20 °C to 25 °C).
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Advancements in materials innovation requires much research and development in the electrolyte selection and improving the anode resistance to plating.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] One such materials innovation would be to add other compounds to the electrolyte like fluoroethylene carbonate (FEC) to form a rich LiF SEI.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Another novel method would be to coat the separator in a protective shield that essentially "kills" the lithium ions before it can form these dendrites.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Certain manganese containing cathodes can degrade by the Hunter degradation mechanism resulting in manganese dissolution and reduction on the anode.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] By the Hunter mechanism for LiMn 2O 4, hydrofluoric acid catalyzes the loss of manganese through disproportionation of a surface trivalent manganese to form a tetravalent manganese and a soluble divalent manganese: 2Mn3+ → Mn2++ Mn4+ Material loss of the spinel results in capacity fade.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Temperatures as low as 50 °C initiate Mn2+ deposition on the anode as metallic manganese with the same effects as lithium and copper plating.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Cycling over the theoretical max and min voltage plateaus destroys the crystal lattice via Jahn-Teller distortion, which occurs when Mn4+ is reduced to Mn3+ during discharge.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Storage of a battery charged to greater than 3.6 V initiates electrolyte oxidation by the cathode and induces SEI layer formation on the cathode.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] As with the anode, excessive SEI formation forms an insulator resulting in capacity fade and uneven current distribution.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Storage at less than 2 V results in the slow degradation of LiCoO 2 and LiMn 2O 4 cathodes, the release of oxygen and irreversible capacity loss.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Discharging below 2 V can also result in the dissolution of the copper anode current collector and, thus, in catastrophic internal short-circuiting on recharge.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The IEEE standard 1188–1996 recommends replacing lithium-ion batteries in an electric vehicle, when their charge capacity drops to 80% of the nominal value.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In what follows, we shall use the 20% capacity loss as a comparison point between different studies.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p01] We shall note, nevertheless, that the linear model of degradation (the constant % of charge loss per cycle or per calendar time) is not always applicable, and that a "knee point", observed as a change of the slope, and related to the change of the main degradation mechanism, is often observed.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The problem of lithium-ion battery safety was recognized even before were first commercially released in 1991.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The two main reasons for lithium-ion battery fires and explosions are related to processes on the negative electrode (anode when discharging, cathode when charging).
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] During a normal battery charge lithium ions intercalate into graphite.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] However, if the charge is too fast or the temperature is too low lithium metal starts plating on the negative electrode, and the resulting dendrites can penetrate the battery separator, internally short-circuit the cell, and result in high electric current, heating and ignition.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] In other mechanisms, an explosive reaction between the negative electrode material (LiC6) and the solvent (liquid organic carbonate) occurs even at open circuit, provided that the electrode temperature exceeds a certain threshold above 70 °C.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Lithium-ion batteries in the 18650 format or larger may incorporate safety mechanisms such as a current interrupt device (CID) and a positive temperature coefficient (PTC) device.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The CID consists of two metal disks in electrical contact.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] When internal pressure increases, the disks separate, breaking the circuit and terminating the current.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The PTC device is composed of a conductive polymer; an increase in current causes the polymer to heat, increasing its electrical resistance and reducing the current flow.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Lithium-ion batteries can be a safety hazard since they contain a flammable electrolyte and may become pressurized if they become damaged.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] A battery cell charged too quickly could cause a short circuit, leading to overheating, explosions, and fires.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] 4. internal short circuit, e.g. due to manufacturing flaws or aging.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Because of these risks, testing standards are more stringent than those for acid-electrolyte batteries, requiring both a broader range of test conditions and additional battery-specific tests, and there are shipping limitations imposed by safety regulators.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] There have been battery-related recalls by some companies, including the 2016 Samsung Galaxy Note 7 recall for battery fires.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Lithium-ion batteries have a flammable liquid electrolyte.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] A faulty battery can cause a serious fire.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Faulty chargers can affect the safety of the battery because they can destroy the battery's protection circuit.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] While charging at temperatures below 0 °C, the negative electrode of the cells gets plated with pure lithium, which can compromise the safety of the whole pack.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Short-circuiting a battery will cause the cell to overheat and possibly to catch fire.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Smoke from thermal runaway in a Li-ion battery is both flammable and toxic.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Batteries are tested according to the UL 9540A fire standard, and the TS-800 standard also tests fire propagation from one battery container to adjacent containers.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] UPS Airlines Flight 6 crashed in Dubai after its payload of batteries spontaneously ignited.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] To reduce fire hazards, research projects are intended to develop non-flammable electrolytes.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] If a lithium-ion battery is damaged, crushed, or subjected to a higher electrical load without having overcharge protection, problems may arise.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] External short circuit can trigger a battery explosion.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Such incidents can occur when lithium-ion batteries are not disposed of through the appropriate channels, but are thrown away with other waste.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The way they are treated by recycling companies can damage them and cause fires, which in turn can lead to large-scale conflagrations.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Twelve such fires were recorded in Swiss recycling facilities in 2023.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] If overheated or overcharged, Li-ion batteries may suffer thermal runaway and cell rupture.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] During thermal runaway, internal degradation and oxidization processes can keep cell temperatures above 500 °C, with the possibility of igniting secondary combustibles, as well as leading to leakage, explosion or fire in extreme cases.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] To reduce these risks, many lithium-ion cells (and battery packs) contain fail-safe circuitry that disconnects the battery when its voltage is outside the safe range of 3–4.2 V per cell, or when overcharged or discharged.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Lithium battery packs, whether constructed by a vendor or the end-user, without effective battery management circuits are susceptible to these issues.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Poorly designed or implemented battery management circuits also may cause problems; it is difficult to be certain that any particular battery management circuitry is properly implemented.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Lithium-ion cells are susceptible to stress by voltage ranges outside of safe ones between 2.5 and 3.65/4.1/4.2 or 4.35 V (depending on the components of the cell).
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Exceeding this voltage range results in premature aging and in safety risks due to the reactive components in the cells.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] When stored for long periods the small current draw of the protection circuitry may drain the battery below its shutoff voltage; normal chargers may then be useless since the battery management system (BMS) may retain a record of this battery (or charger) "failure".
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Many types of lithium-ion cells cannot be charged safely below 0 °C, as this can result in plating of lithium on the anode of the cell, which may cause complications such as internal short-circuit paths.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] These features are required because the negative electrode produces heat during use, while the positive electrode may produce oxygen.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] However, these additional devices occupy space inside the cells, add points of failure, and may irreversibly disable the cell when activated.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Further, these features increase costs compared to nickel metal hydride batteries, which require only a hydrogen/oxygen recombination device and a back-up pressure valve.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Contaminants inside the cells can defeat these safety devices.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Also, these features can not be applied to all kinds of cells, e.g., prismatic high-current cells cannot be equipped with a vent or thermal interrupt.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] High-current cells must not produce excessive heat or oxygen, lest there be a failure, possibly violent.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Instead, they must be equipped with internal thermal fuses which act before the anode and cathode reach their thermal limits.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Replacing the lithium cobalt oxide positive electrode material with a lithium metal phosphate such as lithium iron phosphate (LFP) improves cycle counts, shelf life and safety, but lowers capacity.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] As of 2006, these safer lithium-ion batteries were mainly used in electric cars and other large-capacity battery applications, where safety is critical.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] In 2016, an LFP-based energy storage system was chosen to be installed in Paiyun Lodge on Mt.Jade (Yushan) (the highest lodge in Taiwan).
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] As of June 2024, the system was still operating safely.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] In 2006, approximately 10 million Sony batteries used in laptops were recalled, including those in laptops from Dell, Sony, Apple, Lenovo, Panasonic, Toshiba, Hitachi, Fujitsu and Sharp.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The batteries were found to be susceptible to internal contamination by metal particles during manufacture.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Under some circumstances, these particles could pierce the separator, causing a dangerous short circuit.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] IATA estimates that over a billion lithium metal and lithium-ion cells are flown each year.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Some kinds of lithium batteries may be prohibited aboard aircraft because of the fire hazard.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Some postal administrations restrict air shipping (including EMS) of lithium and lithium-ion batteries, either separately or installed in equipment.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] In 2023, most commercial Li-ion batteries employed alkylcarbonate solvents to assure the formation solid electrolyte interface on the negative electrode.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Since such solvents are readily flammable, there has been active research to replace them with non-flammable solvents or to add fire suppressants.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Another source of hazard is hexafluorophosphate anion, which is needed to passivate the negative current collector made of aluminium.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Hexafluorophosphate reacts with water and releases volatile and toxic hydrogen fluoride.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Several strategies have been explored for developing non-flammable Li-ion battery electrolytes.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] One approach uses fluorinated (co-)solvents, such as methyl-(2,2,2-trifluoroethyl)-carbonate (FEMC) or methyl-3,3,3-trifluoropropionate (MTFP).
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Another approach uses fluorinated anions, such as lithium bis(trifluoromethanesulfonyl)imide or lithium difluoro(oxalato)borate in high concentrations.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] As of 2021, almost 90% of raw lithium extraction originated from three countries: Australia (53%), Chile (24%), and China (10%), with almost all production coming from China (56%), Chile (32%) and Argentina (11%).
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Extraction of lithium, nickel, and cobalt, manufacture of solvents, and mining byproducts present significant environmental and health hazards.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Lithium extraction can be fatal to aquatic life due to water pollution.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] It is known to cause surface water contamination, drinking water contamination, respiratory problems, ecosystem degradation and landscape damage.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] It also leads to unsustainable water consumption in arid regions (1.9 million liters per ton of lithium).
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Massive byproduct generation of lithium extraction also presents unsolved problems, such as large amounts of magnesium and lime waste.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Lithium mining takes place in North and South America, Asia, South Africa, Australia, and China.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Cobalt for Li-ion batteries is largely mined in the Congo (see also Mining industry of the Democratic Republic of the Congo).
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Open-pit cobalt mining has led to deforestation and habitat destruction in the Democratic Republic of Congo.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Open-pit nickel mining has led to environmental degradation and pollution in developing countries such as the Philippines and Indonesia.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] In 2024, nickel mining and processing was one of the main causes of deforestation in Indonesia.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Manufacturing a kg of Li-ion battery takes about 67 megajoules (MJ) of energy.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The global warming potential of lithium-ion batteries manufacturing strongly depends on the energy source used in mining and manufacturing operations, and is difficult to estimate, but one 2019 study estimated 73 kg CO2e/kWh.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Effective recycling can reduce the carbon footprint of the production significantly.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The Li-ion battery recycling rate is often misconstrued to be 5%, in reality, insufficient research exists to determine the exact figure.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The European Union estimates 49% of portable batteries sold were collected for recycling in 2023, whilst the UK estimates 45% as of 2026.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] New EU legislation requires 70% of collected Li-ion battery material to be recovered through recycling by 2031, which must include recovery rates of 80% for lithium and 95% for cobalt, nickel, and manganese; however, no recycled lithium has re-entered the EU as of 2023.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] These measures aim to aid sustainability efforts and reduce pressure on raw material extraction, as demand for lithium and cobalt is expected to increase 8-fold by 2040, far exceeding current production capabilities.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Most research focuses on the recovery of active materials, especially lithium which is a critical raw material; however, through advanced recycling techniques and more sustainable design considerations, electrolytes, binders, and separators can also recycled.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Recycling is a multi-step process, starting with the storage of batteries before disposal, followed by manual testing, disassembling, and finally the chemical separation of battery components.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Re-use of the battery is preferred over complete recycling as there is less embodied energy in the process.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] As these batteries are a lot more reactive than classical vehicle waste like tire rubber, there are significant risks to stockpiling used batteries.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The pyrometallurgical method uses a high-temperature furnace to reduce the components of the metal oxides in the battery to an alloy of Co, Cu, Fe, and Ni.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] This is the most common and commercially established method of recycling and can be combined with other similar batteries to increase smelting efficiency and improve thermodynamics.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The metal current collectors aid the smelting process, allowing whole cells or modules to be melted at once.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The product of this method is a collection of metallic alloy, slag, and gas.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] At high temperatures, the polymers used to hold the battery cells together burn off and the metal alloy can be separated through a hydrometallurgical process into its separate components.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The slag can be further refined or used in the cement industry.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The process is relatively risk-free and the exothermic reaction from polymer combustion reduces the required input energy.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] However, in the process, the plastics, electrolytes, and lithium salts will be lost.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] This method involves the use of aqueous solutions to remove the desired metals from the cathode.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The most common reagent is sulfuric acid.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Factors that affect the leaching rate include the concentration of the acid, time, temperature, solid-to-liquid-ratio, and reducing agent.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Once leached, the metals can be extracted through precipitation reactions controlled by changing the pH level of the solution.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Cobalt, the most expensive metal, can then be recovered in the form of sulfate, oxalate, hydroxide, or carbonate.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] More recently, recycling methods experiment with the direct reproduction of the cathode from the leached metals.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] In these procedures, concentrations of the various leached metals are premeasured to match the target cathode and then the cathodes are directly synthesized.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The main issues with this method, however, are the large volume of solvent required and the high cost of neutralization.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Although it is easy to shred up the battery, mixing the cathode and anode at the beginning complicates the process, so they will also need to be separated.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Unfortunately, the current design of batteries makes the process extremely complex and it is difficult to separate the metals in a closed-loop battery system.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Shredding and dissolving may occur at different locations.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Direct recycling is the removal of the cathode or anode from the electrode, which are then reconditioned and reused in a new battery.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Mixed metal-oxides can be added to the new electrode with very little change to the crystal morphology.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The process generally involves the addition of new lithium to replenish the loss of lithium in the cathode due to degradation from cycling.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Cathode strips are obtained from the dismantled batteries, then soaked in NMP, and undergo sonication to remove excess deposits.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] It is treated hydrothermally with a solution containing LiOH/Li2SO4 before annealing.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] This method is extremely cost-effective for noncobalt-based batteries as the raw materials do not make up the bulk of the cost.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Direct recycling avoids the time-consuming and expensive purification steps, which is great for low-cost cathodes such as LiMn2O4 and LiFePO4.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] For these cheaper cathodes, most of the cost, embedded energy, and carbon footprint is associated with the manufacturing rather than the raw material.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] It is experimentally shown that direct recycling can reproduce similar properties to pristine graphite.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The drawback of the method lies in the condition of the retired battery.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] In the case where the battery is relatively healthy, direct recycling can cheaply restore its properties.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] However, for batteries where the state of charge is low, direct recycling may not be worth the investment.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The process must also be tailored to the specific cathode composition, and therefore the process must be configured to one type of battery at a time.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Lastly, in a time with rapidly developing battery technology, the design of a battery today may no longer be desirable a decade from now, rendering direct recycling ineffective.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Physical materials separation recovered materials by mechanical crushing and exploiting physical properties of different components such as particle size, density, ferromagnetism and hydrophobicity.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Copper, aluminum and steel casing can be recovered by sorting.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The remaining materials, called "black mass", which is composed of nickel, cobalt, lithium and manganese, need a secondary treatment to recover.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] For the biological metals reclamation or bio-leaching, the process uses microorganisms to digest metal oxides selectively.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Then, recyclers can reduce these oxides to produce metal nanoparticles.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Although bio-leaching has been used successfully in the mining industry, this process is still nascent to the recycling industry and plenty of opportunities exists for further investigation.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Electrolyte recycling consists of two phases.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The collection phase extracts the electrolyte from the spent Li-ion battery.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] This can be achieved through mechanical processes, distillation, freezing, solvent extraction, and supercritical fluid extraction.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Due to the volatility, flammability, and sensitivity of the electrolyte, the collection process poses a greater difficulty than the collection process for other components of a Li-ion battery.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The next phase consists of separation/electrolyte regeneration.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Separation consists of isolating the individual components of the electrolyte.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] This approach is often used for the direct recovery of the Li salts from the organic solvents.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] In contrast, regeneration of the electrolyte aims to preserve the electrolyte composition by removing impurities which can be achieved through filtration methods.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The recycling of the electrolytes, which consists 10–15 wt.% of the Li-ion battery, provides both economic and environmental benefits.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] These benefits include the recovery of the valuable Li-based salts and the prevention of hazardous compounds, such as volatile organic compounds (VOCs) and carcinogens, being released into the environment.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Compared to electrode recycling, less focus is placed on recycling the electrolyte of Li-ion batteries due to lower economic benefits and greater process challenges.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Such challenges can include the difficulty associated with recycling different electrolyte compositions, removing side products accumulated from electrolyte decomposition during its runtime, and removal of electrolyte adsorbed onto the electrodes.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Due to these challenges, current pyrometallurgical methods of Li-ion battery recycling forgo electrolyte recovery, releasing hazardous gases upon heating.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] However, due to high energy consumption and environmental impact, future recycling methods are being directed away from this approach.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Extraction of raw materials for lithium-ion batteries may present dangers to local people, especially land-based indigenous populations.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Cobalt sourced from the Democratic Republic of the Congo is often mined by workers using hand tools with few safety precautions, resulting in frequent injuries and deaths.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Pollution from these mines has exposed people to toxic chemicals that health officials believe to cause birth defects and breathing difficulties.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Human rights activists have alleged, and investigative journalism reported confirmation, that child labor is used in these mines.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Development of the Thacker Pass lithium mine in Nevada, USA has been met with protests and lawsuits from several indigenous tribes who have said they were not provided free prior and informed consent and that the project threatens cultural and sacred sites.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Links between resource extraction and missing and murdered indigenous women have also prompted local communities to express concerns that the project will create risks to indigenous women.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Protestors have been occupying the site of the proposed mine since January, 2021.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Researchers are actively working to improve the power density, safety, cycle durability (battery life), recharge time, cost, flexibility, and other characteristics, as well as research methods and uses, of these batteries.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Solid-state batteries are being researched as a breakthrough in technological barriers.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Currently, solid-state batteries are expected to be the most promising next-generation battery, and various companies are working to popularize them.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Research areas for lithium-ion batteries include extending lifetime, increasing energy density, improving safety, reducing cost, and increasing charging speed, among others.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Research has been under way in the area of non-flammable electrolytes as a pathway to increased safety based on the flammability and volatility of the organic solvents used in the typical electrolyte.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Strategies include aqueous lithium-ion batteries, ceramic solid electrolytes, polymer electrolytes, ionic liquids, and heavily fluorinated systems.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] One of the ways to improve batteries is to combine the various cathode materials.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] This allows researchers to improve on the qualities of a material, while limiting the negatives.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] One possibility is coating lithium nickel manganese oxide with lithium iron phosphate through resonant acoustic mixing.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The resulting material benefits from an increase electrochemical performance and improved capacity retention.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Similar work was done with iron (III) phosphate.
[src:lithium-battery-management/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Advances in anionic redox understanding have led to stabilization strategies like surface fluorination, improving cycling stability and safety.
[src:lithium-battery-management/state-of-charge] In a battery electric vehicle (BEV), the state of charge indicates the remaining energy in the battery pack.
[src:lithium-battery-management/state-of-charge] The state of charge can help to reduce electrical car owners' anxiety when they are waiting in the line or stay at home since it will reflect the progress of charging and let owners know when it will be ready.
[src:lithium-battery-management/state-of-charge] However on any vehicle dashboard, especially in plug-in hybrid vehicles, the state of charge presented as a gauge or percentage value may not be representative of a real level of charge.
[src:lithium-battery-management/state-of-charge] A noticeable amount of energy may be reserved for hybrid-work operations.
[src:lithium-battery-management/state-of-charge] Examples of such cars are Mitsubishi Outlander PHEV (all versions/years of production), where a charge level of zero is indicated to the driver when the real charge level is 20–22%.
[src:lithium-battery-management/state-of-charge] Another one is the BMW i3 REX (Range Extender version), where about 6% of SoC is reserved for PHEV-alike operations.
[src:lithium-battery-management/state-of-charge] State of charge is also known to impact battery aging.
[src:lithium-battery-management/state-of-charge] To extend battery lifetime, extremes of state of charge should be avoided and reduced variations windows are also preferable.
[src:lithium-battery-management/state-of-charge] Usually, SoC cannot be measured directly but it can be estimated from direct measurement variables in two ways: offline and online.
[src:lithium-battery-management/state-of-charge] In offline techniques, the battery desires to be charged and discharged in constant rate such as Coulomb-counting.
[src:lithium-battery-management/state-of-charge] This method gives precise estimation of battery SoC, but they are protracted, costly, and interrupt main battery performance.
[src:lithium-battery-management/state-of-charge] Therefore, researchers are looking for some online techniques.
[src:lithium-battery-management/state-of-charge] This method works only with batteries that offer access to their liquid electrolyte, such as non-sealed lead acid batteries.
[src:lithium-battery-management/state-of-charge] The specific gravity of the electrolyte can be used to indicate the SoC of the battery.
[src:lithium-battery-management/state-of-charge] Hydrometers are used to calculate the specific gravity of a battery.
[src:lithium-battery-management/state-of-charge] To find specific gravity, it is necessary to measure out volume of the electrolyte and to weigh it.
[src:lithium-battery-management/state-of-charge] Then specific gravity is given by (mass of electrolyte [g]/ volume of electrolyte [ml])/ (Density of Water, i.e.
[src:lithium-battery-management/state-of-charge] To find SoC from specific gravity, a look-up table of SG vs SoC is needed.
[src:lithium-battery-management/state-of-charge] Refractometry has been shown to be a viable method for continuous monitoring of the state of charge.
[src:lithium-battery-management/state-of-charge] The refractive index of the battery electrolyte is directly relatable to the specific gravity or density of the electrolyte of the cell.
[src:lithium-battery-management/state-of-charge] Notably, analysis of electrolyte does not provide information about the state-of-charge in the case of lithium-ion batteries and other batteries, that do not produce or consume solvent or dissolved species during their operation.
[src:lithium-battery-management/state-of-charge] This method converts a reading of the battery voltage to SoC, using the known discharge curve (voltage vs.
[src:lithium-battery-management/state-of-charge] However, the voltage is more significantly affected by the battery current (due to the battery's electrochemical kinetics) and temperature.
[src:lithium-battery-management/state-of-charge] This method can be made more accurate by compensating the voltage reading by a correction term proportional to the battery current, and by using a look-up table of battery's open circuit voltage vs. temperature.
[src:lithium-battery-management/state-of-charge] In fact, it is a stated goal of battery design to provide a voltage as constant as possible no matter the SoC, which makes this method difficult to apply.
[src:lithium-battery-management/state-of-charge] For batteries, that have voltage independent on their state-of-charge (such as lithium iron phosphate battery), open-circuit voltage measurements cannot provide a reliable estimate of the SoC.
[src:lithium-battery-management/state-of-charge] On the other hand, batteries with a sloping voltage-charge curves (such as nickel-cobalt-manganese battery), are more amenable to SoC estimation from the open-circuit voltage measurements.
[src:lithium-battery-management/state-of-charge] This method, also known as *coulomb counting*, calculates the SoC by measuring the battery current and integrating it in time.
[src:lithium-battery-management/state-of-charge] Maxim Integrated touts a combined voltage and charge approach that is claimed superior to either method alone; it is implemented in their ModelGauge m3 series of chips, such as MAX17050, which is used in the Nexus 6 and Nexus 9 Android devices, for example.
[src:lithium-battery-management/state-of-charge] To overcome the shortcomings of the voltage method and the current integration method, a Kalman filter can be used.
[src:lithium-battery-management/state-of-charge] The battery can be described with an electrical model which the Kalman filter will use to predict the over-voltage given the observed current.
[src:lithium-battery-management/state-of-charge] In combination with coulomb counting, it can make an accurate estimation of the state of charge.
[src:lithium-battery-management/state-of-charge] The strength of this technique is that a Kalman filter adjusts its relative trust of the battery voltage and coulomb counting in real time.
[src:lithium-battery-management/state-of-charge] This method can be used with certain NiMH batteries, whose internal pressure increases rapidly when the battery is charged.
[src:lithium-battery-management/state-of-charge] More commonly, a pressure switch indicates if the battery is fully charged.
[src:lithium-battery-management/state-of-charge] This method may be improved by taking into account Peukert's law which is a function of charge/discharge current.
